  footnotes: []
english:
  title: To Jo
  author: Yu Suk
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When will you gather at my hall,
    Where we drink together in harmony,
    Speaking of the joys of riverside villages?

    By day, staff in hand, I walk where mountains frame themselves like paintings.
    By night, through gauzy curtains, moonlight floods across my bed.

    May my writings aid the virtue of the ancient sages,
    Not mimic the silver tongues of cunning speakers.

    Friends are both beloved and to be feared—
    Their hearts vast as mountains and seas,
    Truly beyond all measure.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'The poem plays on the classical scholar''s dual role: contribution through moral writing versus mere eloquence. Yao and Shun represent ideal ancient sage-kings; Su Qin and Zhang Yi were famous Warring States-era persuaders known for manipulation rather than virtue.'
  - key: ''
    value: The moonlight imagery mirrors the dual nature of friendship itself—beauty and intimacy alongside the weight of genuine fellowship.
